      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "**Methodology and Results**\n\nTo evaluate the drought resistance of our novel crop strain, B-42, we employed a controlled, field-based experiment. We cultivated B-42 and a control group under identical conditions, with the exception of a 3-week drought treatment. The experiment was conducted in a climate-controlled greenhouse, where the ambient temperature and relative humidity were maintained at 25.0°C ± 0.5°C and 60.0% ± 2.0%, respectively.\n\nThe crop water retention was measured using a 0.01 m³ water meter, which recorded a 15.0% increase in water retention (ΔW = 0.0150 ± 0.0005 m³/m³) compared to the control group (ΔW = 0.0000 ± 0.0005 m³/m³) during the 21-day drought treatment. The yield of B-42 was consistently maintained at 90.0% ± 1.0% of the control group's yield, even during the prolonged drought period.\n\nRoot depth analysis revealed a significant increase in root growth, with an average root depth of 10.2 cm ± 0.5 cm for B-42, compared",
      "source": "target",
